The most important outcome of the IYDP, however, was the adoption of the World Programme of Action concerning Disabled Persons (WPA) by the United Nations General Assembly in its Resolution 37/52 of 3 December 1982. The purposes of the WPA included, inter alia, the realisation of the goals of full and equal participation of disabled persons in social life and development. General Assembly Resolution 37/53 of 3 December 1982 proclaimed the period 1983–1992 as the United Nations Decade of Disabled Persons – a long-term plan of action to implement the WPA. The WPA is essentially a global strategy directed towards the equalisation of opportunities for persons with disabilities, emphasising the need to approach disability from a human rights perspective. In the educational context, the WPA observed that, although persons with disabilities had the same right to education as non-disabled persons, numerous problems prevented the former group from more fully realising such right, including:
                  

the lack of compulsory education and specialised services and facilities in developing countries;
                  
                  

the lack of legislation and/or policies addressing their specific educational needs;
                  
                  

the shortage of appropriately trained teaching staff.
                  
               The WPA also addressed the finely balanced question of integrated instruction within a regular school setting versus individualised instruction through intensive special education programmes. A ‘presumption of integration’, however, dominates the observations and recommendations of the WPA, as is evidenced in the following passage:
